Let´s talk about some possibly better knews than expected here. No question, that this will end above 200K, and no question that many experts are talking about billions of infected people in the next year/s with millions dying and shutdowns happening everywhere. But I see one thing, that gives me hope (of course also hoping, that the reason isn´t just the lack of testing kits and also fearing bad briers on all the other questions related to corona, I´m in): daily growth rates are not increasing further in the regions I analysed (with my homecountry germany the only bigger exception in Europe (where this is currently growing fastest)). China, South Korea, Japan, Hong Kong, Singapore have all been relatively stable for a while now. Growth in most countries in Europe isn´t as bad as it was in the last days. Although we have got 162 of about 200 countries in the world on the list now, it looks like even the numbers of the worst growing countries on worldometers could stop growing at 20%+ per day with growth even declining in many places. There are some worries, just looking at todays numbers: Malaysia, Pakistan, parts of South Amerika have huge growth rates today, and there as well as in Africa the medical situation might not be perfect. But the overall picture looks better today. I wish, it was true and @ddorsey , as we were on the same pessimistic track for a while so far, would see it the same way (being right with optimistic views feels better than with pessimistic ones !). In spite of the expert´s theories about 50-80% worldwide infection rates - now I really hope, that the chimp will win this. The worldometers data at least is getting better for it ;-) I´d prefer positive responses to my little optimism (after having felt quite beat down from the UK governments analysis (my father is 76, and it really sounded like "all above 70 are in greatest danger" to me) yesterday) from you as well: @Prognosticating-Beek @Dillyweed @ManuPV @Greyowlsova @dlaiocean @Anneinak

Using a small sample set AND averages can be helpful and dangerous, but without a more comprehensive modeling tool, I hopped over to Excel. The final outcome will be limited to our WHO situation report on 20 MAR. That said, based on their numbers, I was curious as to if there was a trend to the new case DoD delta. Increasing to 70%. Assuming this question ends at 0300 EST on 20 March, then there are about 108 hrs (4.5 days) to go. The last 6 days have averaged over 8k new cases per day, so assuming a lineal trend, we can expect about 36k new cases before time on this question runs out. It's going to be very close, though. Per the Johns Hopkins site, there are presently ~163k cases, which means that adding 36k gets us to 199k before this question ends. My estimate of 70% in the +200k category is based on a continuation of the current exponential (vice lineal) trend. If there's an add of 5% per day (as opposed to just a lineal 8k), then we cross the 200k mark just before time runs out,.

To explain as I did in my first forecast: I am using the Logistic Distribution function to model S-Curve (cumulative) cases. This is the system dynamic of disease propagation as explained by many including Dr. John Sterman of MIT (see Business Dynamics, and the original work in System Dynamics by MIT Prof. Jay Forrester). Regardless, multiple iterations of solutions can provide a reasonable estimate.

I've taken a fairly close look at the growth of new cases inside and outside China. Chinese cases have been decreasing in recent weeks, and averaging less than 500 over the past five days. I have updated my forecast to include data in the past six days. The reduction in cases per day has been dramatic. This is not consistent with the Logistics model. The progression is not characteristically smooth. This pattern existed immediately before the Chinese NHC revised its cases to include non-RNA test observations. Again, given the scale of the outbreak, the data suggests that the NHC is not able to collect all of the case information and report accurately. As such, further adjustments seem likely. However, given that the current data suggests the third tipping point of the Logistics model has been achieved, it is more likely that <100,000 case is possible. My model presently forecasts ~80,000 cases total, but again I anticipate under-reporting. I have adjusted downward, but anticipate the highest likelihood between 100,000-200,000 cases by March 20. To explain as I did in my first forecast: I am using the Logistic Distribution function to model S-Curve (cumulative) cases. This is the system dynamic of disease propagation as explained by many including Dr. John Sterman of MIT (see Business Dynamics, and the original work in System Dynamics by MIT Prof. Jay Forrester). The function is fitted to a line using the GRG algorithm in Excel Solver. However, this method is not without difficulty as an optimum point is not provided by the Logistics Distribution function. Regardless, multiple iterations of solutions can provide a reasonable estimate.

I'd like to address some confusion about the reported numbers: people are citing 71K cases (from unofficial data) while WHO in February 16 update cites two sets of numbers right now – 51,857 total and 69,267 (68,584 in China + 683 outside) cases. After the update for today, WHO will have the second number close to 71K as well – bureaucratic channels are always slower. The difference between numbers is that China now includes clinically diagnosed cases - lesions in both lungs by CT plus other symptoms – in their count while WHO at this point recognizes only laboratory confirmed cases - confirmed by DNA testing (e.g. PCR), but for the big picture reports clinically diagnosed cases as well. I should stress that BOTH sets of numbers are INCORRECT as they both differ from the real numbers of infections: laboratory confirmed cases do not include clinical cases that were not confirmed by PCR because of the lack of kits, samples, logistics, personnel… And clinically diagnosed cases may include cases NOT caused by COVID-19 - pneumonias with other etiology. And both numbers will not include mild cases when people did not get to the hospital and recovered at home or otherwise ignored, deliberately or not. So BOTH reported numbers are just approximations: most probably, the higher number is closer to the truth.

I am using the Logistic Distribution function to model S-Curve (cumulative) cases. This is the system dynamic of disease propagation as explained by many including Dr. John Sterman of MIT (see Business Dynamics, and the original work in System Dynamics by MIT Prof. Jay Forrester). The function is fitted to a line using the GRG algorithm in Excel Solver. However, this method is not without difficulty as an optimum point is not provided by the Logistics Distribution function. Regardless, multiple iterations of solutions can provide a reasonable estimate. At present my estimate is ~140,000 cases (after the recent change in reporting).

"For all infectious diseases, the flawed path associated with the average growth rate systematically underestimates the severity early in the epidemic (before month 12 in the above example) and overestimates the severity later in the epidemic (after month 12). For this example, in month 9, you expected 5% of the population to be infected, but on average you will observe 10%. Then at month 18, you expected 35% but only observed 30%. Although a single case does not win a statistical argument, the Ebola epidemic of 2014-2015 fits the bill perfectly. It started out with fears of “We’re all going to die! Used daily confirmed case count from China National Health Center + current world cases as of 1/30/2020. I then built a stochastic SIR type model to project the cases forward to the total cumulative confirmed cases. Currently the rest of the world (ROW) accounts for only about 1% of the total, so I extrapolated China's case counts forward. Since we are still within the exponential phase of the epidemic, I expect to update my predictions regularly based on new case counts as they come in.
